SIMPLE: scalper
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scalper
<hw>Scalper</hw> <pr>(sk⟦acr⟧lp"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who, or that which, scalps.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>Same as <cref>Scalping
iron</cref>, under <er>Scalping</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A broker who, dealing on his own account, tries to
get a small and quick profit from slight fluctuations of the
market.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person who buys and sells the unused parts of
railroad tickets.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><--<sn>5.</sn> <def>A person who buys tickets for entertainment or
sports events and sells them at a profit, often at a much higher price.
Also, <altname>ticket scalper</altname>.</def>
<mark>[Cant]</mark>-->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scalping</ent>⟦br⟧
